### Create a new assessment Array
POST http://localhost:8080/api/assessments HTTP/1.1
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "id": "array-list-1",
  "category": "array-list",
  "questions": [
    {
      "text": "How do you access the value (5) in this array nums?",
      "image_url": "/assessment/array-list/q1.png",
      "type": "multiple_choice",
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "That's right! Since array indices start at 0, the fifth element (the value 5) is at index 4.",
        "incorrect": "Not quite. Arrays start counting from 0, so the fifth element is actually at index 4."
      },
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "nums[3]",
          "is_correct": false
        },
        {
          "text": "nums[3]",
          "is_correct": false
        },
        {
          "text": "nums[4]",
          "is_correct": true
        },
        {
          "text": "nums[5]",
          "is_correct": false
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "text": "For items = [\"Sword\", \"Shield\", \"Potion\"], how do you access the very first element?",
      "image_url": null,
      "type": "multiple_choice",
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Correct! In almost all programming languages, arrays are 0-indexed. The first element is always at index 0.",
        "incorrect": "Careful! Computer scientists start counting at 0. If you use [1], you\u00e2\u20ac\u2122ll actually grab the second item (Shield)!"
      },
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "items[1]",
          "is_correct": false
        },
        {
          "text": "items[0]",
          "is_correct": true
        },
        {
          "text": "items{0}",
          "is_correct": false
        },
        {
          "text": "items{1}",
          "is_correct": false
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "text": "In a Dynamic Array, what happens behind the scenes when you add an element but the capacity is full?",
      "image_url": null,
      "type": "multiple_choice",
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Correct! This is why \"pushing\" to a dynamic array is usually O(1), but occasionally becomes O(n) during a resize.",
        "incorrect": "A dynamic array is still just a basic array under the hood. Since a basic array is a fixed block of slots, it can't just \"grow\" if the spots next to it are taken. It must find a brand-new, larger space and move everything there."
      },
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "The array expands into the next available byte.",
          "is_correct": false
        },
        {
          "text": "The computer allocates a larger block and copies all elements over.",
          "is_correct": true
        },
        {
          "text": "The array becomes a Linked List automatically.",
          "is_correct": false
        },
        {
          "text": "The new element is stored in an 'overflow' variable.",
          "is_correct": false
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "text": "Which operation is faster: accessing Index 0 or accessing a random middle element (Index 547)?",
      "image_url": null,
      "type": "multiple_choice",
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Correct! This is the power of the Address Calculation Formula. Whether the index is 0 or 547, the computer performs the same single math operation to find the address instantly (O(1)).",
        "incorrect": "It\u00e2\u20ac\u2122s a trick! Remember the formula: Address = Base + (Index * Size). The computer does the same amount of 'work' regardless of how big the index is."
      },
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Index 0 is faster",
          "is_correct": false
        },
        {
          "text": "Index 547 is slower",
          "is_correct": false
        },
        {
          "text": "Both take the exact same amount of time",
          "is_correct": true
        },
        {
          "text": "It depends on the stored value",
          "is_correct": false
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "text": "Which of the following operations is the most efficient (fastest) in a standard array?",
      "image_url": null,
      "type": "multiple_choice",
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Excellent! Accessing by index is O(1) constant time. It takes the same amount of time whether you have 10 elements or 10 million.",
        "incorrect": "Think about which operation lets the computer jump directly to the answer. Most of these require looking at or shifting every item in the list."
      },
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Inserting at the beginning",
          "is_correct": false
        },
        {
          "text": "Searching in an unsorted array",
          "is_correct": false
        },
        {
          "text": "Accessing an item at a specific index",
          "is_correct": true
        },
        {
          "text": "Deleting from the middle",
          "is_correct": false
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "text": "Why is inserting in the middle of an array slower than adding at the end?",
      "image_url": null,
      "type": "multiple_choice",
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Exactly! To maintain the order, every element after the new item must be 'scooted over' to make room.",
        "incorrect": "Not quite. Think about the slots. If you put something in slot 5, what has to happen to the items already in slots 5, 6, and 7?"
      },
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Arrays only allow insertions at the start/end",
          "is_correct": false
        },
        {
          "text": "Elements after the insertion point must be shifted",
          "is_correct": true
        },
        {
          "text": "The array must reallocate memory every time",
          "is_correct": false
        },
        {
          "text": "Middle elements are locked in place",
          "is_correct": false
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "text": "Worst-case search time for a specific username in an unsorted array of 1,000,000 elements?",
      "image_url": null,
      "type": "multiple_choice",
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Correct! Because it's unsorted, you might have to check every single element. This is Linear Search (O(n)).",
        "incorrect": "If the computer doesn't know where the value is, it has to check one-by-one. If the item is at the very end, how many steps does that take?"
      },
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "O(1)",
          "is_correct": false
        },
        {
          "text": "O(n)",
          "is_correct": true
        },
        {
          "text": "O(n\u00c2\u00b2)",
          "is_correct": false
        },
        {
          "text": "O(log n)",
          "is_correct": false
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "text": "Given a character array starting at base address 1024 where each character occupies 1 byte, what is the memory location of the character at index 7?",
      "image_url": null,
      "type": "multiple_choice",
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Correct! Each index increases the address by 1 byte: 1024 + 7 = 1031.",
        "incorrect": "Careful with the 'off-by-one' error. If index 0 is 1024, count 7 steps forward. (1024 + 7)."
      },
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "1030",
          "is_correct": false
        },
        {
          "text": "1031",
          "is_correct": true
        },
        {
          "text": "1032",
          "is_correct": false
        },
        {
          "text": "1033",
          "is_correct": false
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "text": "What does the index in an array represent?",
      "image_url": null,
      "type": "multiple_choice",
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "That's right! The index is the offset from the start of the array.",
        "incorrect": "The index is like a mailbox number. It tells you *where* to look, not *what* is inside the box."
      },
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "The position (offset) of an element",
          "is_correct": true
        },
        {
          "text": "The actual value stored inside",
          "is_correct": false
        },
        {
          "text": "The frequency of the value",
          "is_correct": false
        },
        {
          "text": "The total size of the array",
          "is_correct": false
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "text": "Given an array of integers starting at base address 2000 where each integer occupies 4 bytes, what is the memory location of the element at index 5?",
      "image_url": null,
      "type": "multiple_choice",
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Correct! Using Base + (Index * Size): 2000 + (5 * 4) = 2020.",
        "incorrect": "Use the Address Calculation formula: Address = Base + (Index * Size). You need to skip five 4-byte elements from the starting address of 2000."
      },
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "2005",
          "is_correct": false
        },
        {
          "text": "2016",
          "is_correct": false
        },
        {
          "text": "2020",
          "is_correct": true
        },
        {
          "text": "2024",
          "is_correct": false
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}


### Get a single assessment with questions and choices
GET http://localhost:8080/assessments/array-list/array-list-1 HTTP/1.1
